                                        <h2 class="title">Youth Mental Health</h2>
                                        <p class="description mt--30">Youth mental health is an increasingly important issue that affects young people all around the world. Mental health problems such as anxiety, depression, and substance abuse can have a significant impact on a young person's development, social relationships, and academic success.</p>
                                        <p class="description">Early identification and intervention are crucial in managing youth mental health issues and promoting positive mental health and well-being. Despite this, stigma and discrimination surrounding mental health remain significant barriers for young people seeking help. It is important to create supportive environments and provide access to mental health services to ensure that young people can get the help they need.</p>
                                    </div>
                                    
                                    <div class="portfolio-details-btn mt--30"><a class="btn-default btn-border" href="https://www.nami.org/Blogs/NAMI-Blog/February-2023/Ask-Dr-Christine-Youth-Mental-Health">Blog Site</a></div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="col-lg-6">
                                <div class="portfolio-details-accordion mt_md--40 mt_sm--40">
                                    <div class="inner">
                                        <div class="section-title">
                                            <h4 class="title">Content</h4>
                                            <p class="description mt--30">Youth mental health is a critical issue that can have serious consequences if not addressed. Common problems affecting youth mental health include depression, anxiety, substance abuse, eating disorders, self-harm, and suicide.</p>
                                            <p class="description mt--30">It is important to provide young people with access to mental health services and to encourage open communication about their feelings and experiences. Identifying and addressing these issues early on can help prevent long-term mental health problems and improve the overall well-being of young people.</p>
                                            <ul class="list-style--1">
                                                <li><i data-feather="check"></i> Mental health issues are prevalent among youth: Mental health problems are increasingly common among young people today. According to the World Health Organization, around 10-20% of children and adolescents worldwide experience mental disorders. These disorders can include anxiety, depression, substance abuse, eating disorders, and self-harm behaviors, among others.</li>
                                                <li><i data-feather="check"></i> Early intervention is crucial: Early identification and intervention are crucial in managing youth mental health issues. When mental health concerns are addressed early on, it can prevent the problems from escalating into more severe issues that can negatively impact a young person's development and well-being.</li>
                                                <li><i data-feather="check"></i> Stigma is a significant barrier to seeking help: Stigma and discrimination surrounding mental health remain significant barriers for young people seeking help. Many young people may feel ashamed or embarrassed to admit they are experiencing mental health problems, leading them to suffer in silence. This stigma can be particularly harmful to young people, who may feel isolated and unsupported.</li>
                                                <li><i data-feather="check"></i> Supportive environments can promote positive mental health: Creating supportive environments for young people can promote positive mental health and well-being. This can include providing access to mental health services, creating safe and inclusive spaces, and offering resources and support to those who may be struggling. By fostering a culture of openness and acceptance, young people can feel more comfortable seeking help when they need it.</li>
                                            </ul>
                                        </div>
